PO wrote:<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> I read in an article that single stage nuclear launchers would be reusable.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Could you provide a reference for that statement? Are you aware of what a reuseable atomic launch vehicle equal, say, to the space shuttle would be like in power output, radioactive emission, and fission product buildup?<br>
<br>
Just as a hint, the largest nuclear engine (briefly) fired had a power output of 2 full-sized (unshielded, and uncontainered) atomic power plants. It was the most powerful artificial atomic reactor ever made. As a rocket engine, it thrusted (briefly) at 250,000 pounds. For comparison, the Space Shuttle is about 7,000,000 pounds of thrust. Therefore an equivalent cluster of atomic engines wore equal roughly 56 atomic power plants in energy output and fallout production. This would be the same as boosting the entire French nuclear capacity in an unsheilded, uncontainered machine flying up through the atmosphere and arching across most of the globe.<br>
<br>
I would really like a citation for a source describing such a machine.<br>
