Reliability of your engines also affects costs.  If you hard start engine every 1000 minutes (like the ssme[space shuttle] engines did during testing) your costs understandably skyrocket. A &quot;hard start&quot; is an industry euphemism like &quot;spontaneous self disassembly&quot; that means you blew up an engine.<br>
<br>
If you're really serious about learning about rocket propulsion, I recommmend the book &quot;ignition&quot; by john clark.  you can find it on amazon.com here<br>
<br>
&quot;<!--EZCODE AUTOLINK START--><a href="http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/0813507251/qid%3D1028427824/sr%3D11-1/ref%3Dsr%5F11%5F1/103-7956873-1604605"">www.amazon.com/exec/obido...3-1604605"</a><!--EZCODE AUTOLINK END--><br>
<br>
It'll be reasonably expensive(50 bucks or so) but its well worth it in my opinion.  Everything he says holds true today since rocket propulsion research stopped in the late 60's / early 70's.  <br>
