<br>
do you have documentation for all the stuff you listed? You threw out quite a few numbers there, and I'm curious to see source listings for a couple reasons.<br>
<br>
1) Factual information with valid sources is always good to know.<br>
<br>
2) I'm already seeing a discrepancy.You stated that it would take 8 civilian power plants for 16 Gigawatts of electricty.  As a simple conversion, 16 GWt would be 16000 MWt.  This would mean each reactor would be producing 2000 MWt by your numbers.  I don't know of a single reactor right now that produces that much power in the world, quite honestly.  A typical BWR produces ~500-600 MWt, PWRs on average produce ~1000-1300 MWt.  4th gen plants like the PBMR work by having smaller designs and producing ~300-400 MWt.  There are some larger plants being designed by France, but I haven't seen stats on what they would produce.  Regardless, either you number of reactors was off or your electricty rating was off, or both. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/ujohnfraz.showPublicProfile?language=EN>John Fraz</A>&nbsp; <IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_yingyang.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>NERVA Spaceplane Pilot</span><br>  Posts: 162<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(8/7/02 1:09 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=534.topic&index=15>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://lneilsmith.com/tools/littlelogo.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/spaceh.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Nuclear boosters -bad idea</span><hr size=1> I mostly agree that a nuclear booster is a bad idea. Too much dead weight, even if you make it unshielded, unmanned (by necessity if no shielding, and no people on the ground after the nuclear fuel's loaded) and no extra mass for safeties to make sure it won't malfunction and if so, won't spew fallout.<br>
 I could maybe be convinced, if somebody could show me how something llike Clarke's &quot;Orion&quot; NTR spaceplane (from 2001) could be made both 1)lightweight and 2)safe.<br>
<br>
 Truax with the <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.astronautix.com/lvs/searagon.htm">Sea Dragon</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--> also shows that it's just not needed. Kick it in the ass with traditional rockets, but non-traditionally designed.<br>
 See also Pournelle on the <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.jerrypournelle.com/slowchange/SSX.html">SSX</a><!--EZCODE LINK END-->, and the &quot;<!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.fourmilab.ch/documents/rocketaday.html">Rocket a Day</a><!--EZCODE LINK END-->&quot; article. Surprised nobody else here remembered these.<br>
<br>
Most importantly I'm also of the opinion that the same exact hardware in the Shuttle (for example) could provide CATS (relatively cheap, anyway), if you throw out the entire government procurement system.<br>
 Let somebody buy a Shuttle-C or Ares at reasonable prices for aerospace business, and see how much your cost/unit mass to orbit goes down.<br>
<br>
 Zubrin wrote that there's no good engineering reason why a Titan booster costs more than a 747 -not even the fact that it's thrown away after use. You must pay congress-critters, and all the beltway bandits, and all the useless baggage that's involved in a governmental contract process.<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
 I gagged on this (as I've done before with no-nuke ideas)<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>    &gt; I do have other issues with any nuclear rockets<br>
(essentially the encouragement of proliferation by<br>
providing a reason to possess weapons-usable<br>
enriched fissiles.)...</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
 The old idea that the entire technology -the entire idea of enriching nuclear fuels to the point where bomb-grade material is available- should be banned. Dumb down the species so nobody ever again refines fissionables to get a strong neutron source. Eradicate all knowledge of the technology required, shoot physics teachers who might leak it, burn all books with mentions of it -not just specifics of how to do it, but just mentions of it, since somebody could re-invent it. Strong mind-control methods to make sure nobody does an underground teaching class of what's possible in physics. Just shoot them all or brain wash them, since somebody someday might use it to make a bomb.<br>
Go back to the dark ages, where we didn't have any idea of how the Sun works, forget everything we know about how elements are made in Stars, since it might provide a clue.<br>
<br>
 I just don't get the reasoning behind the idea that we can ban all application of the ability to enrich fissionables to get a chain reaction, but we can't ban the act of making killing weapons with it.<br>
<br>
 I challenged this earlier here, and earlier on the old PO club, when it was reported that Taylor, in Dyson's new book, opined that there's still hope for disentangling nuclear power, (and maybe Orion?) from the horror of Hiroshima.<br>
 Isn't there any hope for the idea that nuclear power (yes, and Orion style  NPRs' nuclear explosives) can be used, without being used to kill?<br>
